Good question 👌 — and very important clarification.

Short answer:

❌ Not every expect is mocking.
✅ Mocking specifically means expecting a method to be called on an object.

Let’s break this clearly.

1️⃣ Normal expect (Assertion — NOT Mocking)

Example:

expect(user.name).to eq("Shubham")

This is just checking state/value.

No mocking happening.

Another example:

expect(user).to be_valid

Again → just verifying result.

👉 This is called state-based testing, not mocking.

2️⃣ Mocking = Expecting a Method Call

Mocking happens when you write:

expect(User).to receive(:find).with(1)

Now you are saying:

I expect this method to be called.

If User.find(1) is NOT called → test fails.

That is mocking.

3️⃣ Very Clear Rule
🔹 This is NOT mocking:
expect(result).to eq(10)
🔹 This IS mocking:
expect(SomeClass).to receive(:some_method)

The keyword that indicates mocking is:

receive

Whenever you see:

expect(object).to receive(:method_name)

→ That is mock / message expectation.

4️⃣ What About Stubbing?

Stubbing uses:

allow(object).to receive(:method).and_return(value)

This does NOT fail if method is not called.

So:

Code	Type
expect(x).to eq(y)	Assertion
allow(x).to receive(:m)	Stub
expect(x).to receive(:m)	Mock
5️⃣ Real-World Example (Service Object)

Imagine:

class PaymentProcessor
  def call(user)
    NotificationService.send_email(user)
  end
end

Test:

expect(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email).with(user)
PaymentProcessor.new.call(user)

Now you are testing:

Did this interaction happen?

That is mocking.

6️⃣ Interview-Ready Answer

If interviewer asks:

“What is mocking in RSpec?”

You say:

Mocking is when we set an expectation that a particular method should be called during the test execution, using expect(...).to receive(...). If that method is not called, the test fails.

7️⃣ Very Important Mental Model

There are two testing styles:

🔹 State-based testing

Check data change:

expect(user.balance).to eq(50)
🔹 Interaction-based testing (Mocking)

Check method call:

expect(Gateway).to receive(:charge)
🔥 Final Answer to Your Question

“Whenever expect method is called is it mocking?”

No.

Mocking only happens when you use:

expect(object).to receive(:method)

Normal expect(...).to eq(...) is just assertion.

